      "properties": {
        "Node name for S&R": "Note"
      },
      "widgets_values": [
        "MERGE #3 — Three-way chained merge: Roofs/Facades + Walls + Relief Mesh\n\nScenario: a complex exterior architecture shot with sloped roofs,\nforeground street-level objects, AND a distant background that\nnone of the single-purpose derive nodes covers alone. This is the\n'chain multiple AtlasMergeGeometry instances for 3+-way combination'\ncase referenced in the node's own docstring — worth demonstrating\nexplicitly since the other 2 merge examples are both binary.\n\n1. Branch A (node 4) — AtlasDeriveRoofsFacades: any-orientation\n   planes via sequential RANSAC. Best for sloped roofs/ramps/\n   stepped facades that a flat vertical wall can't represent.\n2. Branch B (node 5) — AtlasDeriveWalls: foreground boxes/\n   cylinders (cars, street furniture, etc.).\n3. Branch C (node 6) — AtlasDeriveReliefMesh: the distant\n   background (sky-adjacent terrain, far rooftops).\n4. Merge 1 (node 7) — combines A + B. solve_a=A provides the\n   camera for this intermediate solve.\n5. Merge 2 (node 8) — combines (A+B) + C. solve_a is the already-\n   merged solve from step 4, so its camera (originally A's) is\n   what survives into the final merged output.\n\nAll three branches read from the SAME AtlasDepthMap (node 3) output\n— this is required for correctness, not just speed: if each branch\nran its own depth pass, their independently-fitted ground scales\ncould disagree slightly, misaligning the merged result."
      ]
    }
